### Result: PASS
- Deletion order (Deployment → Service → Ingress → ConfigMap/Secret/PVC) is safe and correct
- Verification after each step works as documented
- Procedure execution time: ~2 minutes (well under 10 min per SC-002)

## GitOps (ArgoCD) Decommission Path Test (US1)

### Test Setup
- Created Application: sandbox-gitops-test in argocd namespace
- Source: https://github.com/natanbs/sandbox-gitops-test (dummy repo)

### Steps Executed
1. ✅ Pre-checks: Same as Direct Deploy
2. ✅ Application created and confirmed via kubectl get application
3. ✅ Application deleted via kubectl delete application sandbox-gitops-test -n argocd
4. ✅ Verify Application removed: NotFound
5. ✅ Verify no orphaned namespace: NotFound
6. NOTE: Full "remove manifests → commit → ArgoCD prunes" cycle requires git push access
   to the app repo. The documented git commands (git rm, commit, push) were validated
   for correct syntax. The cascade deletion path (deleting the Application directly)
   was validated end-to-end.

### Result: PASS (end-to-end Application lifecycle + verification)
- Partial limitation: Full git-driven prune cycle requires external repo write access

## Container Image Cleanup Test

### Test Setup
- Pushed: localhost:50000/sandbox-test-img:latest
- Registry type: k3d local registry (distributed as Docker Hub registry:2)

### Methods Tested
1. ❌ Registry DELETE API → 405 Method Not Allowed (not supported in registry:2)
2. ❌ regctl (instrumentisto/regctl) → image not found/pull denied
3. ✅ Manual disk removal: docker exec k3d-reg rm -rf /var/lib/registry/... 
   + registry garbage-collect command → image successfully removed
4. ✅ Verified: "NAME_UNKNOWN" response confirms deletion

### Result: PASS (with caveat)
- Procedure correctly notes CLI/API deletion may not be supported
- Recovery guidance: "use web UI or note in audit entry" is accurate
- k3d registry entry could document the disk deletion + GC approach

